---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro';

const baseUrl = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

// Prompts kept as consts so literal braces / angle brackets render verbatim
// (.astro treats { } as expressions — a const string sidesteps all escaping).
const buildPrompt = `Build me a scheduled Patch Drift Reporter agent. Do all of this end to end:

1. Confirm the WYRE MCP Gateway works and Datto RMM is reachable: call
   datto_list_sites and check it returns your managed sites. Record the site
   count for reference only — do NOT bake site IDs into the routine.
2. Confirm a Slack connector is connected. Note the destination channel name
   and ID (e.g. #sw-dev). If Slack does not show in the /schedule connector
   list, read its connector_uuid and url from an existing routine that already
   uses Slack (RemoteTrigger list -> get -> mcp_connections).
3. Create a Claude-managed scheduled routine named "Patch Drift Reporter":
   - Schedule: weekly, cron "0 11 * * 1" (Monday 07:00 America/New_York =
     11:00 UTC). Faster-than-hourly cadences are rejected.
   - Attach TWO connectors, each with permitted_tools populated:
       * WYRE MCP Gateway: datto_list_sites, datto_list_devices,
         datto_get_device, datto_get_device_audit
       * Slack: slack_create_canvas, slack_send_message
     An empty permitted_tools list = the routine runs with no tools.
   - Routine prompt: every run, sweep every Datto RMM site, read each device's
     OS patch status, flag devices more than 30 days behind or in a
     failed/error patch state, build a report grouped by site, publish it as a
     Slack canvas, and post a one-line summary linking the canvas. Use the
     exact routine prompt below.
4. Trigger a manual run and verify: a canvas titled "Patch Drift - <date>" was
   created, a one-line summary landed in the destination channel, and the
   report content matches the live fleet (spot-check one site).`;

const routinePrompt = `You are the Patch Drift Reporter. You run weekly. Keep it lean.

Use ONLY: datto_list_sites, datto_list_devices, datto_get_device,
datto_get_device_audit, slack_create_canvas, slack_send_message.

1. datto_list_sites to get every managed site.
2. For each site, datto_list_devices. For each device, read its OS patch
   status from the device record (use datto_get_device / datto_get_device_audit
   only if patch fields are absent from the list payload).
3. A device is DRIFTED if its last successful patch / OS update is more than
   30 days ago, or patch status is failed/error.
4. Build a report grouped by site: site name, total devices, drifted count,
   and the drifted device names with how far behind each is.
5. slack_create_canvas titled "Patch Drift - <today's date>" with the full
   grouped report. Then slack_send_message to #sw-dev: a one-line summary
   ("Patch drift: N drifted devices across M sites - see canvas") linking it.
6. If a site or device cannot be read, list it in a "could not check" section
   of the report rather than skipping it silently.`;
---
<DocsLayout title="Patch Drift Reporter" description="Build a Claude-managed scheduled agent that sweeps the Datto RMM fleet every week, flags devices behind on patching, and posts a grouped report to Slack as a canvas — no servers, no code.">
  <h1>Patch Drift Reporter</h1>

  <p class="lead text-lg text-[var(--muted)] mb-8">
    A worked example of an <a href={`${baseUrl}advanced-workflows/`}>advanced workflow</a>:
    a Claude-managed scheduled agent that, once a week, sweeps every site in your
    Datto RMM fleet, reads each device's OS patch status, flags everything that has
    drifted past a 30-day threshold, and publishes a site-by-site report to Slack as
    a canvas with a one-line summary. No servers, no code, no deployment — the agent
    is a saved prompt plus a schedule plus two MCP connectors, running in Claude's
    cloud.
  </p>

  <h2 id="what-it-builds">What it builds</h2>
  <p>
    The finished workflow runs unattended on a weekly cron. Each run it enumerates
    managed sites, lists their devices, reasons about which are behind on patching,
    groups the findings by site, and notifies your team — turning a scattered fleet
    into a single prioritised patch-drift report with a Slack trail.
  </p>

  <hr class="my-8" />

  <h2 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h2>
  <p>Before building, your Claude account needs all of the following:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Requirement</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>WYRE MCP Gateway connector</strong></td>
        <td>Connected in claude.ai (<code>https://mcp.wyre.ai/v1/mcp</code>). Provides the <code>datto_*</code> tools. See the <a href={`${baseUrl}getting-started/gateway/`}>Gateway overview</a>.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Datto RMM enabled in the gateway</strong></td>
        <td>The gateway's Datto RMM API user must be able to <strong>read</strong> sites, devices, and device audit data across the fleet.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Slack connector</strong></td>
        <td>The first-party Slack connector connected in claude.ai (<code>https://mcp.slack.com/mcp</code>). Provides <code>slack_create_canvas</code> and <code>slack_send_message</code>.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Scheduled routines access</strong></td>
        <td>Created via the <code>/schedule</code> capability; managed at <a href="https://claude.ai/code/routines" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">claude.ai/code/routines</a>.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>A destination Slack channel</strong></td>
        <td>e.g. <code>#sw-dev</code>, plus its channel ID. The Slack connector must have access to it.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <hr class="my-8" />

  <h2 id="gotchas">Known gotchas</h2>
  <p>
    These are the things that cost real time the first time through. Account for them
    up front and the build genuinely takes minutes.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>One-hour minimum cadence.</strong> Claude-managed routines reject any cron
      faster than hourly — <code>*/5 * * * *</code> fails outright. A weekly sweep is
      well within bounds; just don't try to push it toward real time.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong><code>permitted_tools</code> must be populated per connector.</strong> A
      routine with a connector attached but an empty <code>permitted_tools</code> list
      runs with <em>no tools</em> and silently does nothing — no error, no output. List
      the exact tool names the routine needs.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Don't make the routine call <code>list_*</code> discovery tools you don't
      need.</strong> <code>datto_list_sites</code> and <code>datto_list_devices</code> are
      the working set here and must run every sweep — that is fine. The rule is to never
      bake in <em>extra</em> discovery calls just to look up static IDs; discover those
      once at build time instead.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A routine reaches only its attached connectors.</strong> The routine
      sandbox blocks arbitrary network egress, so notifications must go through the
      Slack connector's tools, not an outbound webhook. Attach every connector the
      workflow touches.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Portfolio sweeps are large — keep the per-device read minimal.</strong>
      A full fleet can be hundreds of devices. Read patch status from the
      <code>datto_list_devices</code> payload wherever possible and avoid calling
      <code>datto_get_device_audit</code> per device unless the list payload genuinely
      lacks patch data — a per-device audit call across the whole fleet risks the
      60-second tool timeout and a stalled run.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <hr class="my-8" />

  <h2 id="build-prompt">The one-shot build prompt</h2>
  <p>
    With the connectors above in place, paste this to Claude. It confirms the gateway,
    creates the routine, and verifies it end to end.
  </p>
  <pre class="not-prose"><code>{buildPrompt}</code></pre>

  <hr class="my-8" />

  <h2 id="routine-prompt">The resulting routine prompt</h2>
  <p>
    This is the lean prompt the build process installs into the scheduled routine itself.
    Substitute your own destination channel.
  </p>
  <pre class="not-prose"><code>{routinePrompt}</code></pre>

  <hr class="my-8" />

  <h2 id="how-it-works">How it works</h2>
  <h3>A weekly cadence, by design</h3>
  <p>
    Patch drift is a slow-moving signal — devices fall behind over days and weeks, not
    minutes. The routine runs every Monday morning so the report is waiting before the
    week's remediation work starts. A weekly cron is also kind to the API: one full
    fleet sweep per week, not one per hour.
  </p>
  <h3>The 30-day threshold is the whole rule</h3>
  <p>
    A device is "drifted" if its last successful OS update is more than 30 days ago, or
    its patch status is failed or error. That single threshold is the entire
    classification logic — no per-OS exceptions, no severity tiers. It keeps the report
    consistent week to week and the routine prompt short. Tune the number to your
    patching SLA.
  </p>
  <h3>Delivery is a Slack canvas plus a summary</h3>
  <p>
    The full site-by-site report can be long, so the routine publishes it as a Slack
    canvas — a durable document teammates can scroll and reference — and posts only a
    one-line summary to the channel linking it. The channel stays readable; the detail
    lives in the canvas. See <a href={`${baseUrl}advanced-workflows/delivery-adapters/`}>delivery adapters</a>
    for other ways to surface a routine's output.
  </p>

  <hr class="my-8" />

  <h2 id="extending">Extending it</h2>
  <p>
    The workflow is RMM-agnostic. To run the same patch-drift sweep against a NinjaOne
    fleet, swap the <code>datto-rmm</code> tools for the gateway's <code>ninjaone</code>
    tools — the org/device enumeration and the per-device patch read map directly, and
    the report-building, threshold, and Slack-delivery body of the routine are
    identical. The gateway exposes the tools; the workflow is just the prompt.
  </p>
  <p class="text-sm text-[var(--muted)]">
    Questions or a workflow you'd like documented?
    <a href="https://github.com/wyre-technology/msp-claude-plugins/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open an issue</a>
    in the <code>msp-claude-plugins</code> repository.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
